{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} {{Infobox scientist | name= Chris Dobson | image = Christopher Dobson (14059418563).jpg | birth_name = Christopher Martin Dobson | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1949|10|08}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = Cambridge | nationality = | field = {{Plainlist| * [[Chemistry]] * [[Biophysics]] * [[Protein folding]]}} | work_institution = {{Plainlist| * [[St John's College, Cambridge]] * [[University of Cambridge]] * [[Harvard University]]}} | alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[University of Oxford]] (BA, DPhil)}} | doctoral_advisor = | thesis_title = The conformation of lysozyme in solution | thesis_url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.453735 | thesis_year = 1975 | doctoral_students = | known_for = | prizes = {{Plainlist| * [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] * [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] * [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences|FAAS]] * [[Davy Medal]] (2005) * [[Royal Medal]] (2009) * [[Heineken Prize]] (2014)}} | website = {{URL|http://www.ch.cam.ac.uk/person/cmd44}} | footnotes = }} Sir '''Christopher Martin Dobson''', [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] (born 8 October 1949) is a British [[chemistry|chemist]], who is the John Humphrey Plummer Professor of [[Chemical biology|Chemical]] and [[Structural Biology]] in the [[Department of Chemistry, University of Cambridge|Department of Chemistry]] at the [[University of Cambridge]], and Master of [[St John's College, Cambridge]].<ref name=cv/><ref name=microsoft>{{AcademicSearch|3116244}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Dobson was born on 8 October 1949.<ref name=Who>{{Who's Who | surname = DOBSON | othernames = Prof. Christopher Martin | id = U13819 | volume = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He was educated at Hereford Cathedral Junior School, and then [[Abingdon School]] from 1960 until 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1968_January_V014_N004.pdf#page=58|title=Chemistry Prizes|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> He completed a [[Bachelor of Arts]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil]]<ref name=dobsondphil>{{cite thesis |degree=DPhil |first=Christopher Martin|last=Dobson |title=The conformation of lysozyme in solution |publisher=University of Oxford |date=2014 |url=https://www.google.com|authorlink=Chris Dobson}}</ref> at the [[University of Oxford]] ([[Keble College, Oxford|Keble]] and [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton Colleges]]).
==Research== Dobson's research is largely concerned with [[protein folding|protein folding and misfolding]], and its links with medical disorders particularly Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases. His research interests are focused on protein molecules, and particularly on defining the fundamental principles by which they fold to generate function and biological activity, and yet can misfold to generate toxicity and disease. His studies are highly interdisciplinary and collaborative, and make use of a very wide range of techniques, encompassing theory as well as experiment. The Dobson group based at the [[Department of Chemistry, University of Cambridge]] <ref name=cv/> is particularly interested in the discovery of the nature, properties, mechanism of formation and biological significance of the ‘misfolded’ amyloid state of proteins. Amyloid-related diseases include whole-body disorders such as the systemic amyloidoses, neuronal disorders such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases, and other organ-specific disorders such as type II diabetes. The major goals are the elucidation of the general molecular principles that underlie this whole family of medical conditions, which are now becoming a major threat to human health and social harmony across the modern world, and the generation of a firm foundation for the rational and effective prevention and treatment of these debilitating and usually fatal conditions.<ref name=cv/> Dobson is an author or co-author of nearly 700 papers and review articles, including more than 30 in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' and ''[[Science (magazine)|Science]]'', which have been cited over 50,000 times. His current [[h-index]] is 110.<ref name=scopus>{{Scopus|id=36042495400}}</ref>
==Career== Dobson held Research Fellowships at Merton College and then [[Linacre College, Oxford|Linacre College]] before working at [[Harvard University]]. He returned to Oxford in 1980 as a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Fellow]] of [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] and as a University Lecturer in Chemistry, later receiving promotions to [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]], then Professor, of Chemistry.<ref name=Who/> Dobson has been at Cambridge since 2001 and has been Master of St John's College, Cambridge since 2007.
==Awards and honours== In 2009 Dobson was awarded the [[Royal Medal]] by the Royal Society "for his outstanding contributions to the understanding of the mechanisms of protein folding and mis-folding, and the implications for disease", and in 2014 he received both the Heineken Prize for Biochemistry and Biophysics and the [[Feltrinelli Prize|Feltrinelli International Prize]] for Medicine. Dobson was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS)]] in 1996. His nomination reads: {{centered pull quote|Dobson is distinguished for his studies, principally using [[Nuclear magnetic resonance|NMR methods]], of the structures and dynamics of proteins in solution. Such studies include those on [[lysozyme]], with which he demonstrated many methodological advances, [[Interleukin 4|interleukin-4]], with which he established for the first time the topology of the important family of [[Haematopoiesis|haemopoietic]] helical [[cytokine]]s, and [[urokinase]]-type [[plasminogen activator]], with which he elucidated the dynamic characteristics of multidomain [[Fibrinolysis|fibrinolytic proteins]], Dobson is a pioneer in the application of NMR methods to the problem of protein folding, which is now the major theme of his work. His studies on lysozyme are resulting in one of the most detailed descriptions of a folding pathway for a protein. Dobson has explored the properties and reactions of molecules in solids by means of NMR spectroscopy, including [[protein]]s, [[Organometallic chemistry|organometallic compounds]], [[inorganic]] [[Paramagnetism|paramagnets]] and the silicaceous components of hydraulic materials. Notable here are analyses of the nature and origin of dynamic properties in molecular solids, and their relationship to structure and reactivity.<ref name=royal>{{cite web |url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo==%27EC%2F1996%2F06%27) |title=EC/1996/06: Dobson, Christopher Martin |publisher=The Royal Society |archivedate=30 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SyQujALd?url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=%28RefNo%3D%3D%27EC%2F1996%2F06%27%29 |location=London |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all |access-date=30 September 2014 }}</ref>}}
