{{Redirect|Gay propaganda|the 2013 Russian law|Russian gay propaganda law}} '''Homosexual agenda''' (or '''gay agenda''') is a term introduced by sectors of the [[Christian right|Christian religious right]] (primarily [[Social conservatism in the United States|in the United States]]) as a disparaging way to describe the [[LGBT social movements|advocacy of cultural acceptance and normalization]] of [[non-heterosexual]] [[Sexual orientation|orientations]] and relationships. The term refers to efforts to change government policies and laws on [[LGBT rights]]-related issues. Additionally, it has been used by social conservatives and others to describe alleged goals of LGBT rights activists, such as [[homosexual recruitment|recruiting heterosexuals]] into what they term a "[[homosexual lifestyle]]".<ref name="thinkprogress.org">[http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2012/07/09/512916/hate-group-homosexual-activists-try-to-confuse-children-to-build-their-numbers/ Hate Group: 'Homosexual Activists' Try To 'Confuse Children' To 'Build Their Numbers'] ''[[Think Progress]]'' July 9, 2012. *[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/15/us/ugandan-gay-rights-group-sues-scott-lively-an-american-evangelist.html Ugandan Gay Rights Group Sues U.S. Evangelist] *[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/22/bryan-fischer-gay-rights-abortion-environmentalism_n_1619128.html Bryan Fischer Slams Gay Rights, Abortion And Environmentalism As 'The Work Of Satan Himself'] *[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/06/caiden-cowger-teen-radio-host-gay-obama_n_1574524.html Caiden Cowger, Conservative Teen Radio Host, Slams President Obama For "Making Kids Gay"] *[http://www.metroweekly.com/2010/01/anti-gay-maryland-legislator-e/ Anti-gay Maryland legislator, Emmett Burns, moves again to cut off recognition of out-of-state gay marriages] *{{cite news|url=http://onenewsnow.com/Culture/Default.aspx?id=1371064|title='Gay' indoctrination a reality|last=Yeh|first=Becky|date=June 16, 2011|work=OneNewsNow|accessdate=June 25, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110618020032/http://www.onenewsnow.com/Culture/Default.aspx?id=1371064|archivedate=June 18, 2011|df=}}</ref>
== Origins and usage of the term "gay agenda" == [[File:Gaymarchwash.jpg|thumb|Cover of DVD ''The Gay Agenda: March on Washington'']]
===Early usage=== In the [[United States]], the phrase "the gay agenda" was popularized by a video series produced by the evangelical religious group, Springs of Life Ministries in California, and distributed by many [[Christian Right]] organizations, the first video of which was called ''The Gay Agenda'' and was released in 1992.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Herman|first=Didi|title=The Anti-Gay Agenda: Orthodox Vision and the Christian Right|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year= 1997 (ebook, 2007)|isbn=9780226327693|ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|81-81}} In the same year the [[Oregon Citizens Alliance]] (a conservative Christian political activist organization) used this video as part of their campaign for [[Oregon Ballot Measure 9 (1992)|Ballot Measure 9]] to amend the Oregon Constitution to prevent what the OCA called [[special rights]] for gays, [[lesbian]]s, and [[bisexual]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Signorile|first=Michelangelo|year=1993|title=Queer In America|ref=harv}}</ref>
[[Paul Cameron]]—co-founder of the Institute for the Scientific Investigation of Sexuality in Lincoln, later renamed the [[Family Research Institute]]—appeared in the video, wherein he asserted that 75 percent of gay men regularly ingest [[feces]] and that 70–78 percent have had a [[sexually transmitted disease]].<ref>{{harv|Herman|1998|p=78}}</ref> ''The Gay Agenda'' was followed by three other video publications; ''The Gay Agenda in Public Education'' (1993), ''The Gay Agenda: March on Washington'' (1993) and a feature follow-up ''Stonewall: 25 Years of Deception'' (1994). The videos contained interviews with [[LGBT rights opposition|opponents of LGBT rights]], and the series was made available through [[Christian right]] organizations.<ref>{{harv|Herman|1998|pp=80–81}}</ref>
The idea of a ''homosexual agenda'' is also used by some Christian critics of LGBT rights in conjunction with a putative ideology they refer to as ''homosexualism'' (as opposed to a synonym for homosexuality), using ''homosexualists'' to describe people who seek to advance LGBT emancipation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sg.christianpost.com/dbase/editorial/330/7%7c15/1.htm|title=''Understanding the Homosexual Agenda'', The Christian Post, Sept 23 2008|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317005543/http://sg.christianpost.com/dbase/editorial/330/7%7C15/1.htm|archive-date=17 March 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anglican-mainstream.net/?p=14100|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904122311/http://www.anglican-mainstream.net/?p=14100|dead-url=yes|archive-date=4 September 2009|title=''Obama Renews His Commitment to the Full Homosexualist Agenda'', Anglican Mainstream, August 18 2009|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> The use of ''homosexualist'' in this way first appeared in 1995 in Scott Lively and Kevin Abrams' book ''[[The Pink Swastika]]'', "to refer to any person, homosexual or not, who actively promotes homosexuality as morally and socially equivalent to heterosexuality as a basis for social policy".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mega.nu:8080/ampp/pinkswastika.hold/book.html|title=''The Pink Swastika'', "A Word to the Reader", Scott Lively and Kevin Abrams, 3rd edition, 1998|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> Lively and Abrahams argue that alleged homosexuality found in the Nazi Party, specifically within [[Ernst Röhm]]'s [[Sturmabteilung|SA]], contributed to the extreme militarism of Nazi Germany, and write about the "gay agenda" in this context.
===Contemporary usage and meaning=== The term is applied to efforts to change government policies and laws on [[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]], and [[transgender]] ([[LGBT]]) issues, for example, [[same-sex marriage]] and [[civil unions]], [[LGBT adoption]], recognizing [[Suspect classification|sexual orientation as a protected civil rights minority classification]], [[Sexual orientation and military service|LGBT military participation]], inclusion of [[LGBT history]] and themes in [[public education]], introduction of [[anti-bullying legislation]] to protect LGBT minors—as well as non-governmental campaigns and individual actions that increase visibility and cultural acceptance of LGBT people, relationships, and identities. The term has also been used by some [[social conservatism in the United States|social conservatives]] to describe alleged goals of [[LGBT rights]] activists, such as supposed [[homosexual recruitment|recruitment]] of heterosexuals into a "homosexual lifestyle".<ref name="thinkprogress.org"/>
A 1987 essay titled "The Overhauling of Straight America", by [[Marshall Kirk]] and Hunter Madsen (writing as Erastes Pill),<ref>{{cite paper |title=The Overhauling of Straight America |url=http://library.gayhomeland.org/0018/EN/EN_Overhauling_Straight.htm |author=Kirk, Marshall and Pill, Erastes (pseud.) |date=1987 |publisher=Guide Magazine}}</ref> lays out a six-point plan for a campaign, which was first published in ''Guide'' magazine. They argued that gays must portray themselves in a positive way to straight America, and that the main aim of making homosexuality acceptable could be achieved by getting Americans "to think that it is just another thing, with a shrug of their shoulders". Then "your battle for legal and social rights is virtually won". The pair developed their argument in the 1989 book ''After the Ball: How America Will Conquer Its Fear and Hatred of Gays in the '90s''. The book outlined a public relations strategy for the LGBT movement. It argues that after the [[gay liberation]] phase of the 1970s and 1980s, gay rights groups should adopt more professional public relations techniques to convey their message. After its publication Kirk appeared in the pages of ''Newsweek'', ''Time'' and ''The Washington Post''. The book is often critically described by social conservatives such as [[Focus on the Family]] as important to the success of the LGBT Movement in the '90s and as part of an alleged "homosexual agenda".<ref name="osten">{{Citation|last=Osten|first=Craig|title=Q&A: The Homosexual Agenda |publisher=CitizenLink, affiliate of [[Focus on the Family]] |year=2003 |url=http://www.citizenlink.org/CLFeatures/A000000562.cfm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080612003916/http://www.citizenlink.org/CLFeatures/A000000562.cfm |archivedate=2008-06-12 |accessdate=2011-03-30}}</ref>
===Other usages=== {{unordered list |In 2003, [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] wrote in his dissent in the landmark case ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'' that
{{quote|Today's opinion is the product of a Court, which is the product of a law-profession culture, that has largely signed on to the so-called homosexual agenda, by which I mean the agenda promoted by some homosexual activists directed at eliminating the moral opprobrium that has traditionally attached to homosexual conduct.<ref>{{harv|Cobb|2006|p=161}}</ref>}}
|In 2004, [[Oklahoma]] Senator [[Tom Coburn]] rated the "gay agenda" as a more pressing danger than any [[terrorist]] activity affecting Americans.<ref group="n" name=Moulitsas>{{cite news |title=Kissing the tarantula: US blogger Markos Moulitsas marvels at the Tories' attempts to woo the gay vote, in stark contrast to the stance of US conservatives |last=Moulitsas |first=Markos |date=May 5, 2005 |publisher=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/may/05/election2005.comment1 |quote=To the newly elected Republican senator from Oklahoma, Tom Coburn, the "gay agenda" is a more pressing danger than terrorists flying planes into buildings and killing allied troops in Iraq. "The gay community has infiltrated the very centres of power in every area across this country, and they wield extreme power ... That agenda is the greatest threat to our freedom that we face today," he said during the 2004 campaign. "Why do you think we see the rationalisation for abortion and multiple sexual partners? That's a gay agenda." }}</ref> |In 2005, [[James Dobson]], director of [[Focus on the Family]], described the homosexual agenda as follows:
{{quote|Those goals include universal acceptance of the gay lifestyle, discrediting of [[Bible|scriptures]] that condemn homosexuality, muzzling of the clergy and Christian media, granting of special privileges and rights in the law, overturning laws prohibiting [[pedophilia]], indoctrinating children and future generations through public education, and securing all the legal benefits of marriage for any two or more people who claim to have homosexual tendencies.<ref>Dobson, Dr. James (2005). "[https://web.archive.org/web/20051006003516/https://www.family.org/docstudy/bookshelf/a0032438.cfm Marriage Under Fire]".</ref><!--dead link?-->}}
|In 2010, American conservative Christian group [[Family Research Council]] produced a graphic labelled "Homosexual Agenda" which consisted of the phrases "Innocence", "Family", "Local Community", "Public Health" and "Parental Authority" struck out with red lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.frc.org/get.cfm?i=WU10F13&f=RF07B06 |accessdate=June 17, 2010 |title=Washington Update |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101028074520/http://www.frc.org/get.cfm?i=WU10F13&f=RF07B06 |archivedate= October 28, 2010}}</ref>}}
== Responses == [[File:Militant Gay Atheist Hugs Rally to Restore Sanity.jpg|thumb|A man satirizing the concept of a gay agenda at the [[Rally to Restore Sanity and/or Fear]].]] The [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] (GLAAD) describes the term as a "rhetorical invention of [[Homophobia|anti-gay]] extremists seeking to create a climate of fear by portraying the pursuit of civil rights for LGBT people as sinister",<ref name=glaad_terms>{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/reference/offensive|title=GLAAD Media Reference Guide: Offensive Terms to Avoid|publisher=GLAAD}}</ref> and commentators have remarked on a lack of realism and veracity to the idea of a gay agenda ''[[wikt:per se|per se]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bouley II |first=Charles Karel |title=The gay agenda revealed! |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |year=2005 |url=http://www.advocate.com/printArticle.aspx?id=43306 |accessdate=February 24, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sa'at|first=Alfian|title=Iced Bandung – What Is The Gay Agenda?|publisher=Trevvy.com|date=March 10, 2007|url=http://www.trevvy.com/scoops/article.php?a_id=221&c_id=3|accessdate=July 9, 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307070930/http://www.trevvy.com/scoops/article.php?a_id=221&c_id=3|archivedate=March 7, 2008|df=}}</ref> Such campaigns based on a presumed "gay agenda" have been described as [[anti-gay propaganda]] by researchers and critics.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Duberman |first=Martin B. |year=1997 |title=A queer world: the Center for Lesbian and Gay Studies reader |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-0-8147-1875-9 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ksbz9vEpzxIC |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Gail |year=1997 |title=Homophobic violence |first2=Stephen |last2=Tomsen |publisher=Hawkins Press |isbn=978-1-876067-04-5 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JS_t92NOMF8C |ref=harv}}</ref> [[GLAAD]] describes the [[pedophilia and homosexuality|association of homosexuality with pedophilia]] or [[child abuse]] as an attempt to "insinuate that lesbians and gay men pose a threat to society, to families, and to children in particular."<ref name=glaad_guide>{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/Document.Doc?id=99 |title=GLAAD Media Reference Guide |publisher=GLAAD |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101043203/http://www.glaad.org/document.doc?id=99 |archivedate=2011-01-01 |df= }}</ref> GLAAD considers assertions linking pedophilia and homosexuality to be defamatory, damaging and entirely inaccurate.<ref name=glaad_guide /> Some writers have described the term as [[pejorative]].<ref name="FoxVirtue2002">{{cite book|author1=F. Earle Fox|author2=David W. Virtue|title=Homosexuality: Good and Right in the Eyes of God?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cbfVg_1qhe0C&pg=PT269|accessdate=June 25, 2012|date=July 1, 2002|publisher=Emmaus Ministries|isbn=978-0-945778-01-1|pages=269–}}</ref>
In a [[press conference]] on December 22, 2010, [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Barney Frank]] said that the "gay agenda" is
{{quote|text=to be protected against violent crimes driven by bigotry, it's to be able to get married, it's to be able to get a job, and it's to be able to fight for our country. For those who are worried about the radical homosexual agenda, let me put them on notice. Two down, two to go.<ref>{{cite web |title=Barney Frank Reveals Gay Agenda |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |year=2010 |url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2010/12/22/barney-frank-reveals-gay-agenda |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>}}
Sportscaster L. Z. Grandersen argues in his TED talk that the "gay agenda" is simply the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|14th Amendment]].<ref>{{cite web | title=The Myth Of The Gay Agenda |url=http://www.ted.com/talks/lz_granderson_the_myth_of_the_gay_agenda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=14th amendment|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/amendmentxiv}}</ref>
=== Satire === A [[satire|satirical]] article by Michael Swift which appeared in the ''[[Gay Community News (Boston)|Gay Community News]]'' in February 1987 entitled "Gay Revolutionary" describes a scenario in which homosexual men dominate [[American society]] and suppress all things heterosexual. This was reprinted in ''[[Congressional Record]]'' without the opening line: "This essay is an outré, madness, a tragic, cruel fantasy, an eruption of inner rage, on how the oppressed desperately dream of being the oppressor."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/pwh/swift1.html|title=Fordham University: Michael Swift – Gay Revolutionary (the complete essay)|publisher=|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>
The term is sometimes used satirically as a counterfoil by people who would normally find this term offensive, such as the spoof agenda found on the [[Betty Bowers]] satirical website,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bettybowers.com/homoagenda.html|title=This website is currently unavailable.|website=www.bettybowers.com|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> and when Bishop [[Gene Robinson]] declared that "Jesus is the agenda, the homosexual agenda in the Episcopal Church".<ref>Bishop Gene Robinson, "[http://www.beliefnet.com/News/2006/06/Jesus-Is-The-Homosexual-Agenda.aspx?p=2 Jesus is the Homosexual Agenda]", address to the General Convention of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, June 14, 2006</ref><ref>"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080717075629/http://www.episcopalchurch.org/79901_98902_ENG_HTM.htm Church need not be afraid, New Hampshire bishop tells Putney gathering]", ''Episcopal Life'', July 13, 2008. "The "homosexual agenda, is Jesus, the Jesus I know who communicates God's unwavering love for me."</ref> On an episode of ''[[The Daily Show]]'', [[Jon Stewart]] defined the gay agenda as "[[gay marriage]], [[civil rights]] protection, [[Fleet Week]] expanded to Fleet Year, [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) assistance for when [[it's raining men]], [[Kathy Griffin]] to host everything and a nationwide ban on [[pleated|pleated pants]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=Jon Stewart spells out the gay agenda|author=Lyle Masaki|url=http://www.afterelton.com/blog/lylemasaki/jon-stewart-spells-out-the-gay-agenda|accessdate=October 14, 2009}}</ref>
