[[File:Huynh Thuc Khang.jpg|thumb|upright|Huỳnh Thúc Kháng]]
'''Huỳnh Thúc Kháng''' ([[History of writing in Vietnam|chữ Hán]]: {{linktext|黃|叔|抗}}; 1 October 1876 – 21 April 1947) was a [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] anti-colonialist and associate of [[Phan Chu Trinh]].

Huỳnh Thúc Kháng born in [[Tiên Phước District]] in [[Quảng Nam Province]], the same district from which Trinh hailed, Khang went on to top the imperial examinations in 1900. In 1946 Kháng came back to Quảng Ngãi to lead the fight against the French in the 5th Interzone. He died the next year in suspicious circumstances.<ref>Hoàng Văn Đào ''Viet Nam Quoc Dan Dang: A Contemporary History '' 2008 "A longtime afterward, Huỳnh Thúc Kháng came back to Quảng Ngãi to lead the fight against the French in the 5th Interzone; there, he learned in secret of the deception at the Head Office. Kháng goggled at this information, but said nothing further. Later, Huỳnh Thúc Kháng died. His death, according to a document by Professor Nguyễn Văn Mùi and Mr. Nguyễn Xuân Chữ, was a suspicious one...."</ref>

Most cities in Vietnam have named major streets after him.<ref>{{cite book| title=Vietnam Country Map |publisher=Periplus Travel Maps |year=2002&ndash;03 |isbn=0-7946-0070-0}}</ref>

